Electric TCS and MBR Agreements Effective Date: 12/31/9998 Rate Schedule FERC No. 1 Option Code A EXHIBIT A GENERATING FACILITY INTERCONNECTION AGREEMENT by and between BASIN ELECTRIC POWER COOPERATIVE and MCKENZIE ELECTRIC COOPERATIVE, INC. December 10, 2013 Generating Facility Interconnection Agreement This Generating Facility Interconnection Agreement (this "Agreement") is entered into and made effective as of this 10th day of December, 2013, by and between McKenzie Electric Cooperative, Inc., a North Dakota electric Cooperative corporation (the "Cooperative") and Basin Electric Power Cooperative, a North Dakota not-for-profit cooperative corporation (the "Customer"). The Cooperative and the Customer are each individually referred to herein as a "Party" and collectively as the "Parties". WITNESSETH: WHEREAS, the Customer intends to develop a generation project (Project) consisting of three (3) GE LM6000 gas-fired electric generators with up to one hundred and fifty (150) megawatts (MW) of aggregate nameplate capacity located in McKenzie County, North Dakota; and WHEREAS, the Customer desires to electrically interconnect the Project (as more particularly defined below) with the Cooperative's electric transmission system, and the Cooperative desires to allow such interconnection on the terms and conditions set forth herein. NOW THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual promises, covenants and conditions contained herein, the Cooperative and the Customer hereby agree as follows: SCOPE OF AGREEMENT: This Agreement shall state the terms and conditions of the interconnection of the Project to the Cooperative's electric transmission system at the Point of Interconnection (as diagramed on Exhibit "A" attached hereto) and shall set forth the requirements and responsibilities of the Parties with respect to such interconnection. LIMITATIONS: This Agreement shall be limited to the interconnection of the Project. This Agreement does not provide for transmission service, energy delivery or control area service arrangements. Such arrangements, including station service, or any transmission, energy delivery or control area service arrangements for electric energy shall require separate contractual arrangements. Nothing in this Agreement stated or otherwise, shall be construed as the Cooperative relinquishing control or diminishing its ability to change, modify, add or utilize Cooperative owned facilities in any way it sees necessary, without approvals from any non-owner of facilities. Furthermore, no entity other than Cooperative may utilize facilities owned by the Cooperative. TERM: The "Term" of this Agreement shall commence on the effective date hereof and continue through the date that the Project ceases commercial operations unless sooner terminated in accordance with the terms hereof. The Parties may mutually agree to terminate this Agreement at any time. The Customer may terminate this Agreement at any time and for any reason by giving written notice to the Cooperative at least thirty (30) days in advance of the effective date of such termination provided, however, that in each case such termination notice shall not relieve either Party of any obligation incurred under this Agreement prior to such termination date. TERMS and DEFINITIONS: Terms used in this Agreement shall have the meanings as listed below. 4.1 Agreement shall have the meaning set forth in the first paragraph hereof. 4.2 Bulk Electric System (BES) shall have the same meaning as the definition contained in the NERC Glossary of Terms. 4.3 Control Area Operator shall mean the Western Area Power Administration (WAPA) or any successor to WAPA, as applicable. 4.4 Cooperative shall have the meaning set forth in the first paragraph hereof. 4.5 Cooperative Interconnection Facilities shall have the meaning set forth in Section 5.2. 4.6 Cooperative's Requirements for Interconnection shall mean the Cooperative's standards for interconnection, attached hereto as Exhibit C. 4.7 Customer shall have the meaning set forth in the first paragraph hereof. 4.8 Customer Interconnection Facilities shall have the meaning set forth in Section 5.2. 4.9 Default shall have the meaning set forth in Section 23.1 4.10 Force Majeure Event shall have the meaning set forth in Section 22.1. 4.11 Good Utility Practice shall mean any of the practices, methods and acts engaged in or approved by a significant portion of the electric industry, in the region, during the relevant time period, or any of the practices, methods and the acts which, in the exercise of reasonable judgment in light of the facts known at the time the decision was made, could have been expected to accomplish the desired result at a reasonable cost consistent with good business practices, reliability, safety and expedition. Good Utility Practice is not intended to be limited to the optimum practice, method, or act to the exclusion of all others, but rather to be acceptable practices, methods, or acts generally accepted in the region. 4.12 Lender or Lenders shall mean any and all Persons or successors in interest thereof lending money or extending credit as follows: (a) for the construction, interim or permanent financing of the Project; (b) for working capital or other ordinary business requirements of the Project (including the maintenance, repair, replacement or improvement of the Project); (c) for any development financing, bridge financing, credit support, credit enhancement or interest rate protection in connection with the Project; (d) for any capital improvement or replacement related to the Project; or (e) for the purchase of the Project and the related rights from the Customer. 4.13 NERC Reliability Standards shall mean those reliability standards as defined by the North American Electric Reliability Corporation (NERC), or its successor, as applicable. 4.14 Person shall mean an individual, partnership, corporation, business trust, joint stock company, trust, unincorporated association, joint venture, governmental entity, limited liability company or any other entity of whatever nature. 4.15 Point of Interconnection shall mean the point, more specifically described in Section 5.1 and diagramed on Exhibit "A", where the Cooperative's electric transmission system electrically connects to the Project. 4.16 Term shall have the meaning set forth in Section 3. 4.17 Transmission System Upgrades shall mean additions, modifications and upgrades to the Cooperative's electric transmission system (other than the Cooperative Interconnection Facilities), the Control Area Operator's electric transmission system or any other electric delivery system beyond the Point of Interconnection to which the Cooperative's electric transmission system or the Control Area Operator's electric transmission system is directly or indirectly interconnected, to accommodate the interconnection of the Project to the Cooperative's electric transmission system. 4.18 Project shall mean the electrical plant and equipment used to generate electricity utilizing natural gas fueled combustion turbines and the transmission interconnection including the step up transformers, used to deliver the electricity to the Point of Interconnection, including any and all additions, replacements or modifications, as more particularly described in Exhibit B. 5. FACILITIES, OWNERSHIP, AND RESPONSIBILITIES: The facilities ownership and responsibilities of the Parties are as described below: 5.1 The Project will be connected to the Cooperative's Hay Butte substation's 115 kV ring bus. The Point of Interconnection shall be the line side terminal pads of the 115kV line disconnect switch installed in the Cooperative's Hay Butte substation, as shown on Exhibit A. 5.2 The interconnection facilities on the Cooperative's side of the Point of Interconnection (the "Cooperative Interconnection Facilities") shall be owned, operated and maintained by the Cooperative, at its own expense. The Cooperative Interconnection Facilities shall be the necessary Hay Butte substation equipment to accommodate this interconnection, e.g. steel take-off structure, current transformers, disconnect switches, a breaker and a half with associated relay modifications and the associated 115kV substation bus work. The interconnection facilities on the Customer's side of the Point of Interconnection (the "Customer Interconnection Facilities") shall be owned, constructed, operated and maintained by the Customer, at its own expense. Exceptions include: (a) The meter at the Hay Butte Substation, labeled as M8 in Exhibit A, which is on the Cooperative side of the Point of Interconnection shall be owned, operated, and maintained by the Customer. If the Cooperative purchases, installs, or commissions this meter it will be at the Customer's expense and; (b) The meter at the Lonesome Creek Station, labeled M7 in Exhibit A, which is on the Customer side of the Point of Interconnection shall be owned, operated, and maintained by the Cooperative. And, (c) The Customer will own, operate, and maintain the Remote Terminal Unit and Communication equipment required by the Control Area Operator within the Hay Butte Substation and Cherry Creek Substation shown in Exhibit D. 5.3 Either Party shall provide prompt written notice to the other Party if it becomes aware of any circumstances that will, or could reasonably expected to, adversely affect (a) the interconnection of the Cooperative's electric transmission system and the Project, (b) the Control Area Operator Interconnection or (c) the delivery of energy from the Project. 5.4 The Customer shall hold the Cooperative harmless from and against incremental costs of expenses incurred by the Cooperative as the result of the Cooperative facilities being characterized as BES facilities due to the interconnection of the Customer's generator. Such facilities include all BES facilities between the Lonesome Creek Station (LCS) and the BES facility of Watford City (WC) as highlighted on Exhibit D. The Cooperative will provide the Customer with all required information, access to facilities, control of facilities, and all other things reasonably required to enable the Customer to completely and accurately comply with NERC requirements with respect to the assets highlighted in Exhibit D. 6. FACILITY DESIGN AND CONSTRUCTION: 6.1 The Cooperative shall plan, design, construct, install and commission the Cooperative Interconnection Facilities, at the Customer's expense, in accordance with Good Utility Practice, and in collaboration and coordination with the Customer. 6.2 The Customer shall plan, design, construct, install and commission the Customer Interconnection Facilities, at its own expense, in accordance with applicable Control Area Operator interconnection studies of the Project, Good Utility Practice, the Cooperative's Requirements for Interconnection set forth in Exhibit C. 6.3 The Cooperative shall have the right to review the design of the Project and/or the Customer Interconnection Facilities and to inspect the Project and/or the Customer Interconnection Facilities prior to interconnecting with the Cooperative's electric transmission system. The Cooperative's review and authorization of the design and interconnection shall not be construed as confirming or endorsing the Customer's design or as warranting the Project or the Customer Interconnection Facilities' safety, durability or reliability. The Cooperative shall not, by reason of such review or lack of review, be responsible for the strength, adequacy or capacity of the Customer's equipment or facilities. 6.4 The Customer shall plan, design, construct, install and commission any modification of the Project and the Customer Interconnection Facilities, at its own expense, in accordance with Good Utility Practice, the Cooperative's Requirements for Interconnection set forth in Exhibit C. 6.5 The Customer shall have the right to review the design of the Cooperative Interconnection Facilities and/or the Cooperative's electric transmission system and to inspect the Cooperative Interconnection facilities and/or the Cooperative's electric transmission system prior to interconnection with the Project. The Customer's review of the design and interconnection shall not be construed as confirming or endorsing the Cooperative's design or as warranting the Cooperative's electric transmission system or the Customer Interconnection Facilities safety, durability or reliability. The Customer shall not, by reason of such review or lack of review, be responsible for the strength, adequacy or capacity of the Cooperative's equipment or facilities. 7 INITIAL TESTING AND INSPECTION: A Cooperative representative(s), at Customer's expense, shall oversee operability checkout on the Customer's equipment, including but not limited to metering, relay settings and tests and protective device operation (including, without limitation, circuit breaker and motor operated disconnects) and the Customer, at its expense, shall make changes and modifications as reasonably required to ensure the safe and reliable operation of its equipment in accordance with Good Utility Practice. Such checkout tests are for the purposes of assuring the protection and operation of the Cooperative's electric transmission system and in no way represent any assurance of protection and operation of the Customer's electric system. Final electrical connections between the Cooperative Interconnection Facilities and the Customer Interconnection Facilities shall be made by the Cooperative. 8. OPERATIONS and MAINTENANCE: 8.1 The Cooperative shall use reasonable efforts to cause its electric transmission system to be operated and maintained in accordance with equipment manufacturer's recommendations, applicable environmental and safety standards, Good Utility Practice, and Control Area Operator requirements. The Cooperative shall have operational control and responsibility of its electric transmission system. The Cooperative shall provide the Customer with timely notification of any equipment operation or condition that the Cooperative reasonably believes is likely to adversely affect the operation, power quality or safety of the Project. 8.2 The Customer shall use reasonable efforts to cause the Project to be operated and maintained in accordance with equipment manufacturer's recommendations, applicable environmental and safety standards, Good Utility Practice, the Cooperative's operating and switching procedures and Control Area Operator requirements. The Customer shall have operational control and responsibility of the Project. The Customer shall provide the Cooperative with timely notification of any equipment operation or condition at the Project that the Customer reasonably believes is likely to adversely affect the operation, power quality or safety of the Cooperative's electric transmission system. 8.3 The Cooperative or its designee may assume control of the Cooperative's interrupting device (which is located at the Cooperative's Hay Butte substation) as needed to isolate the Customer's facilities from the Cooperative's electric transmission system for curtailment purposes as defined in Article 12. 8.4 Each Party shall provide ready and willing access to the other Party, or its designee, to the providing Party's facilities as may be necessary for the requesting Party to perform its obligations hereunder, provided that reasonable advance arrangements are made with the providing Party and that a Party performing work within the boundaries of the other Party's facilities shall abide by the safety rules and procedures applicable to such facilities. All construction, installation, inspection, testing, operation, maintenance and removal of equipment directly associated with the Point of Interconnection by either Party shall be coordinated with the other Party so as to eliminate or minimize any interference with the operation and maintenance of the Project and the Cooperative's electric transmission system. METERING AND COMMUNICATIONS: The Cooperative shall procure, install, and replace if necessary, the appropriate metering at the expense of the Customer. The Customer shall be responsible for the costs associated with the procurement, installation, operation, maintenance and replacement of the telemetry equipment needed to provide data required by the Control Area Operator from the Project to the Cooperative, or its designee, and to the Control Area Operator. REMOVAL OF FACILITIES: Any removal of the Customer Interconnection Facilities installed shall be performed at the expense of the Customer. In the event that this Agreement is terminated or if the Customer no longer needs the Cooperative Interconnection Facilities, the Cooperative Interconnection Facilities shall be restored to a functional reconfiguration condition approved by the Cooperative, which approval shall not be unreasonably withheld. Such reconfiguration of the Cooperative Interconnection Facilities shall be at the expense of the Customer, unless such reconfiguration is the result of a Default of the Cooperative, in which case such reconfiguration shall be at the expense of the Cooperative. POWER QUALITY AND CONTROL AREA OPERATOR REQUIREMENTS: The Customer shall operate at a power factor as requested by the Control Area Operator. In the absence of a specific request, the Customer shall be required to maintain a power factor at the Point of Interconnection between 0.95 per-unit lagging and 0.95 per-unit leading, provided that the Customer shall maintain unity power factor at the Point of Interconnection if requested to do so by the Control Area Operator. 11.2 The Customer shall comply with IEEE Standard 519 and shall not operate equipment that (a) imposes power quality problems upon the Cooperative's electric transmission system that materially interferes with the Cooperative's operations, service to its members, or communications facilities or (b) causes an objectionable voltage flicker to the Cooperative's Customers. If such material interference occurs, upon prior notice thereof from the Cooperative to the Customer, the Customer shall diligently pursue corrective action at its own expense. If the Customer does not take corrective action intended to address the issues identified in the notice from the Cooperative or continues to operate the equipment causing interference without restriction or limit, the Cooperative may disconnect the equipment and/or Project from the Cooperative's electric transmission system until the material interference problem is corrected. 12. CURTAILMENT AND DISCONNECTION: 12.1 The Cooperative, or its designee, may curtail or disconnect or require the disconnection of the Project, in accordance with Good Utility Practice and on an equitable and non-discriminatory basis as follows: To operate, construct, install, maintain, repair, replace, remove or inspect any of the Cooperative's equipment or facilities; In connection with a condition likely to result in significant damage to the Cooperative's equipment or if the Cooperative otherwise deems such curtailment necessary to protect life or property; If the Cooperative is required to do so by the Control Area Operator; If the quality of the power delivered to the Cooperative's facilities does not meet requirements set forth in Article 11; or Upon termination of this Agreement. The Cooperative shall provide the Customer with prior written notice and coordination of any such curtailment or disconnection (Unless such notice and coordination is not practicable under the circumstances). 12.2 The Cooperative shall use its best efforts to schedule the curtailment or disconnection of the Project with the Customer at least two (2) weeks prior to the curtailment or disconnection, by providing prior notice to the Customer of the reasons, timing and expected duration of the curtailment or disconnection. The two (2) week notice requirement in this paragraph shall not apply if in the discretion of Cooperative immediate disconnection is required to protect Cooperative's facilities or for safety of workers or public. In the event of an immediate disconnection, the Cooperative shall immediately notify the Customer's distributed generation group. The Cooperative shall attempt to schedule such curtailment or disconnection to coincide with the scheduled outages of the Project or, if that is not possible, to schedule such curtailment or disconnection during periods that are otherwise convenient for the Customer. Any curtailment or disconnection of the Project shall continue only for so long as reasonably necessary under Good Utility Practice. ANCILLARY SERVICES: The Customer, or third party purchasers of energy from the Project, shall be responsible for obtaining, at the Customer's or such third party purchaser's expense, all ancillary services from the Control Area Operator associated with transporting energy over the Cooperative's electric transmission system, which shall include, but shall not be limited to, scheduling, tagging, system control, dispatch, energy imbalance service, regulation, reactive support and operating reserve. SUCCESSORS AND ASSIGNS: 14.1 Except as otherwise set forth herein, this Agreement is not intended to and shall not create rights of any character whatsoever in favor of any Person other than the Parties, and the obligations herein assumed are solely for the use and benefit of the Parties. This Agreement shall inure to the benefit of and shall bind the Parties hereto and their respective successors and assigns. This Agreement shall not be assigned by either Party without the prior written consent of the other Party, which consent shall not be unreasonably withheld. 14.2 Notwithstanding the foregoing, no consent shall be required for Any assignment of this Agreement by the Customer to any Lenders as collateral security for obligations under the financing documents entered into with such Lenders; Any assignment of this Agreement by the Cooperative to any of its lenders as collateral security for obligations under financing documents entered into with such lenders; or Any assignment by the Lenders to a third party after the Lenders have exercised their foreclosure rights with respect to this Agreement or the Project. 14.3 The Cooperative acknowledges that upon an event of default under any financing documents relating to the Project, any of the Lenders or their designees may (but shall not be obligated to) assume, or cause its designee or a new lessee or purchaser of the Project to assume, all of the interests, rights and obligations of the Customer thereafter arising under this Agreement. 14.4 If the rights and interests of the Customer in this Agreement shall be assumed, sold or transferred as herein provided, and the assuming party shall agree in writing to be bound by and to assume, the terms and conditions hereof and any and all obligations to the Cooperative arising or accruing hereunder from and after the date of such assumption, then the Customer shall be released and discharged from the terms and conditions hereof and each such obligation hereunder from and after such date, and the Cooperative shall continue this Agreement with the assuming party as if such Person had been named as the Customer under this Agreement; provided, however, that if any such Person assumes this agreement as provided herein the Cooperative acknowledges and agrees that such Persons shall not be personally liable for the performance of such obligations hereunder except to the extent of the total interest of the Lenders in the Project. Notwithstanding any such assumption by any of the Lenders or a designee thereof, the Customer shall not be released and discharged from and shall remain liable for any and all obligations to the Cooperative arising or accruing hereunder prior to such assumption. 14.5 This agreement will not be modified in the event that the Customer participates in a regional transmission organization (RTO) or independent transmission system operator (ISO), unless the Parties mutually agree to other mutually beneficial agreements. 14.6 The provisions of this Article 14 are for the benefit of the Lenders as well as the Parties, and shall be enforceable by the Lenders as express third-party beneficiaries hereof. The Cooperative hereby agrees that none of the Lenders, nor any bondholder or participant for whom they may act or any trustee acting on their behalf, shall be obligated to perform any obligation or be deemed to incur any liability or obligation provided in this Agreement on the part of the Customer or shall have any obligation or liability to the Cooperative with respect to this Agreement except to the extent any of them becomes a party hereto pursuant to this Article 14. 15. FINANCING LIENS: 15.1 The Customer, without approval of the Cooperative, may, by security, charge or otherwise encumber its interest under this Agreement for the purposes of financing the development, construction and/or operation of the Project and the Customer Interconnection Facilities. 15.2 If the Customer encumbers its interest under this Agreement as permitted by this Article 15, the following provisions shall apply: The Lenders or their designees shall have the right, but not the obligation, to perform any act required to be performed by the Customer under this Agreement to prevent or cure a Default by the Customer and such act performed by the Lenders or their designees shall be as effective to prevent or cure a Default as if done by the Customer, proved that, if any such Lender or its designee elects to perform any act required to be performed by the Customer under this Agreement to prevent or cure a Default by the Customer, the Cooperative will not be deemed to have waived or relinquished its rights and remedies as provided in this Agreement; The Cooperative shall upon request by the Customer execute statements certifying that this Agreement is unmodified (or, modified and stating the nature of the modification), in full force and effect and the absence or existence (and the nature thereof) of any Default hereunder by the Customer and documents of consent to such assignment to the encumbrance and any assignment to such Lenders; and Upon the receipt of a written request from the Customer or any Lender, the Cooperative at Customer's expense shall execute, or arrange for the delivery of, such certificates, opinions and other documents as may be reasonably necessary in order for the Customer to consummate any financing or refinancing of the Project or any part thereof and will enter into reasonable agreements with such Lender, which agreements will grant certain rights to the Lenders as more fully developed and described in such documents, including (i) this Agreement shall not be terminated (except for termination pursuant to the terms of this Agreement) without the consent of Lender, which consent is not to be unreasonably withheld or delayed, (ii) Lenders shall be given notice of, and the opportunity to cure any breach or Default of this Agreement by the Customer, (iii) if the Lender forecloses, takes a deed in lieu of foreclosure or otherwise exercise its remedies pursuant to any security documents, that (A) the Cooperative shall, at Lender's request, continue to perform all of its obligations hereunder, and Lender or its nominee may perform in the place of the Customer, and may assign this Agreement to another Person in place of the Customer, (B) the Lender shall have no liability under this Agreement except during the period of such Lender's ownership or operation of the Project and (C) the Cooperative shall accept performance in accordance with this Agreement by Lender or its nominee and (iv) that the Cooperative shall make representations and warranties to Lender as Lender may reasonably request with regard to (A) the Cooperative's existence, (B) the Cooperative's authority to execute, deliver and perform this Agreement, (C)the binding nature of the document evidencing the Cooperative's consent to assignment to Lender and this Agreement on the Cooperative and (D) receipt of regulatory approvals by the Cooperative with respect to its execution and performance under this Agreement. 16. REPRESENTATIONS AND WARRANTIES: 16.1 The Customer represents and warrants as follows: The Customer is a not-for-profit, electric cooperative corporation, duly organized, validly existing, and in good standing under the laws of the State of North Dakota, and authorized to conduct business in North Dakota; The Customer has the power and authority to enter into and perform this Agreement and is not prohibited from entering into this Agreement or discharging and performing all covenants and obligations on its part to be performed under and pursuant to this Agreement; The execution and delivery of this Agreement, the consummation of the transactions contemplated herein and the fulfillment of and compliance by the Customer with the provisions of this Agreement will not conflict with or constitute a breach of or a default under or require any consent, license or approval (except for approval by its board of directors or equivalent governing body) that has not been obtained pursuant to any of the terms, conditions or provisions of any law, rule or regulation, any order, judgment, writ, injunction, degree determination, award or other instrument or legal requirement of any court or other agency of government, the documents of formation of the Customer or any contractual limitation, restriction or outstanding trust indenture, deed of trust, mortgage, loan agreement, lease, other evidence of indebtedness or any other agreement or instrument to which the Customer is a party or by which it or any of its property is bound and will not result in a breach of or a default under any of the foregoing; The Customer has taken all such action as may be necessary or advisable and proper to authorize this Agreement, the execution and delivery hereof, and the consummation of transactions contemplated hereby; There is no bankruptcy, insolvency, reorganization or receiverships pending or being contemplated by the Customer, or to its knowledge threatened against the Customer: To the Customer's knowledge, there are no actions, proceedings, judgments, rulings or orders issued by, or pending before any court or other governmental body that would materially adversely affect the Customer's ability to perform its obligations under this Agreement; and This Agreement is a legal, valid and binding obligation of the Customer enforceable in accordance with its terms, except as limited by laws of general applicability limiting the enforcement of creditor's rights or by the exercise of judicial discretion in accordance with general principles of equity. 16.2 The Cooperative represents and warrants as follows: The Cooperative is an electric Cooperative corporation duly organized, validly existing and in good standing under the laws of the State of North Dakota; The Cooperative has the power and authority to enter into and perform this Agreement and is not prohibited from entering into this Agreement or discharging and performing all covenants and obligations on its part to be performing all covenants and obligations on its part to be performed under and pursuant to this Agreement; The Cooperative has taken all action required by applicable law in order to approve, execute and deliver this Agreement; The execution and delivery of this Agreement, the consummation of the transactions contemplated herein and the fulfillment of and compliance by the Cooperative with the provisions of this Agreement will not conflict with or constitute a breach of or a default under or require any consent, license or approval (except for the approvals set forth in Section 26) that has not been obtained pursuant to any of the terms, conditions or provisions of any law, rule or regulation, any order, judgment, writ, injunction, decree, determination, award or other instrument or legal requirement of any court of other agency of government, the documents of formation of the Cooperative or any contractual limitation, restriction or outstanding trust indenture, deed of trust, mortgage, loan agreement, lease, other evidence of indebtedness or any other agreement or instrument to which the Cooperative is a party or by which it or any of its property is bound and will not result in a breach of or a default under any of the foregoing; With the exception of the approvals set forth in Section 26, the Cooperative has taken all such action as may be necessary or advisable and proper to authorize this Agreement, the execution and delivery hereof and the consummation of transactions contemplated hereby; There is no bankruptcy, insolvency, reorganization or receiverships pending or being contemplated by the Cooperative, or to its knowledge threatened against the Cooperative; To the Cooperative's knowledge, there are no actions, proceedings, judgments, rulings or orders issued by, or pending before any court or other governmental body that would materially adversely affect the Cooperative's ability to perform its obligations under this Agreement; and This Agreement is a legal, valid and binding obligation of the Cooperative enforceable in accordance with its terms, except as limited by laws of general applicability limiting the enforcement of creditor's rights or by the exercise of judicial discretion in accordance with general principles of equity. 17. INSURANCE 17.1 Each Party, at its own cost and expense, shall maintain and keep in full force and effect from the date hereof through the later of the date of expiration or termination hereof, the following insurance coverage: (a) If and to the extent necessary, Worker's Compensation Insurance for statutory obligations imposed by applicable state laws, and Employer's Liability Insurance with a minimum limit of one million dollars ($1,000,000) for disease and injury to employees; and (b) Commercial General Liability Insurance, including premises and operations, bodily injury, broad form property damage, products/completed operations, contractual liability and independent contractors protective liability all with minimum combined single limit liability of eight million dollars ($8,000,000). 17.2 Either Party may be permitted to maintain any insurance required by this Article 17 in the form of self-insurance, with the prior written approval of the other Party, which approval shall not be unreasonably withheld. All insurance coverage, other than self-insurance, required by this Agreement shall be issued by an insurer with an A.M. Best's rating of not less than "A-" or such other insurer as is reasonably acceptable to both Parties. 17.3 Within fifteen (15) Days after the date hereof, each Party shall provide to the other Party and thereafter maintain with the other Party a current certificate of insurance or evidence of self-insurance verifying the existence of the insurance coverage required by this Agreement. EXHIBITS: Exhibits attached hereto, are hereby made a part of this Agreement and shall be in force and effect in accordance with its respective terms. NOTICES: Each notice, request, demand, statement or routine communication required or permitted under this Agreement, or any notice or communication that either Party may desire to deliver to the other, shall be in writing and shall be considered delivered when received by the other Party be certified U.S. mail or reputable overnight courier addressed to the other Party at its address indicated below or at such other address as either Party may designate for itself in a written notice to the other Party in accordance with this Section 19. COMPLIANCE WITH LAWS, RULES, AND REGULATIONS: The Parties shall ascertain and comply with applicable local, state or federal law, statute, or regulation which applies to the design, siting, construction, installation, operation or any other aspect of the Project, the Customer Interconnection Facilities the Cooperative's electric transmission system and the Cooperative Interconnection Facilities. FORCE MAJEURE: 22.1 For purposes of this Agreement, a "Force Majeure Event" is any event, which wholly or partly prevents or delays the performance of any obligation arising under this Agreement, but only if and to the extent: such event is not within the reasonable control, directly or indirectly, of the Party affected; such event, despite the exercise of reasonable diligence, cannot be prevented, avoided or overcome by such Party; the Party affected has taken all reasonable precautions and measures in order to avoid the effect of such event on such Party's ability to perform its obligations under this Agreement and to mitigate the consequences thereof; and such event is not the direct or indirect result of a Party's negligence or the failure of such Party to perform any of its obligations under this Agreement or to comply with any applicable law. A Force Majeure Event may include, but not be limited to, any of the following, but only to the extent that it satisfies the preceding requirements: acts of war, terrorism, public disorder, rebellion or insurrection; floods, hurricanes, earthquakes, lightning, storms or other natural calamities; environmental contamination, radioactive contamination or the release of any hazardous waste or materials; explosions or fires; strikes, work stoppages or labor disputes; embargos; and sabotage. 22.2 If a Force Majeure Event prevents a Party from fulfilling any obligations under this Agreement, such Party shall promptly notify the other Party in writing and will keep the other Party informed on a continuing basis as to the scope and duration of the Force Majeure Event. The affected Party shall specify the circumstances of the Force Majeure Event, its expected duration and the steps that the affected Party is taking to mitigate the effect of the event on its performance. The affected Party shall be entitled to suspend or modify its performance of obligations under this Agreement but shall use reasonable efforts to resume its performance as soon as possible. 23. DEFAULT 23.1 A "Default" shall be deemed to have occurred hereunder if: a Party fails to perform its obligation in the time or manner provided in this Agreement; or a Party has (i) commenced a voluntary case under any bankruptcy law, applied for or consented to the appointment of, or the taking of possession by, a receiver, trustee, assignee, custodian or liquidator of all or a substantial part of its assets, (ii) failed, or admitted in writing its inability generally, to pay its debts as such debts become due, (iii) made a general assignment for the benefit of creditors, (iv) been adjudicated bankrupt or has filed a petition or an answer seeking an arrangement with creditors, (v) taken advantage of any insolvency law or shall have submitted an answer admitting the material allegations of a petition in bankruptcy or insolvency proceeding, (vi) become subject to an order, judgment or decree for relief, entered in an involuntary case, without the application, approval or consent of such Party by any court of competent jurisdiction appointing a receiver, trustee, assignee, custodian or liquidator, for a substantial part of any of its assets and such order, judgment or decree shall continue unstayed and in effect for any period of one hundred eighty (180) consecutive Days, (vii) filed a voluntary petition in bankruptcy, (viii) failed to remove an involuntary petition in bankruptcy filed against it within one hundred eighty (180) Days of the filing thereof, or (ix) become subject to an order for relief under the provisions of the United States Bankruptcy Act, 11 U.S.C. § 301. 23.2 No Default shall exist where such failure to discharge an obligation is the result of a Force Majeure Event or the result of an act or omission of the other Party. Upon a Default, the non-defaulting Party shall give written notice of such Default to the defaulting Party. The defaulting Party shall have thirty (30) days from receipt of the Default notice within which to cure such Default; provided, however if such Default is not capable of cure within thirty (30) days, the defaulting Party shall commence such cure within thirty (30) days after notice and continuously and diligently pursue such cure until the Default specified in such notice shall cease to exist. 23.3 If a Default is not cured as provided in Section 23.2, then the non-defaulting Party shall have the right to terminate this Agreement by written notice at any time prior to the cure of the Default. Regardless of whether or not the non-defaulting Party terminates this Agreement, the non-defaulting Party shall have the right to recover from the defaulting Party all amounts due hereunder, plus all other damages and remedies to which it is entitled at law or in equity. The provisions of this Section 23.3 shall survive termination of this Agreement. 23.4 Notwithstanding the foregoing, upon the occurrence of a Default, the non-defaulting Party shall be entitled to (i) commence an action to require the defaulting Party to remedy such Default and specifically perform its duties and obligations hereunder in accordance with the terms and conditions hereof, and (ii) exercise such other rights and remedies as it may have in equity or at law. MCKENZIE ELECTRIC COOPERATIVE By: Title: Date: BASIN ELECTRIC POWER COOPERATIVE By: Title: Date: EXHIBIT A CUI/CEII MATERIAL – DO NOT RELEASE EXHIBIT B DESCRIPTION OF PROJECT Basin Electric intends to build, own and operate a Project consisting of three (3) GE LM6000 machines with an aggregate nameplate capacity rating not to exceed one hundred fifty (150) MW. The Project will be located in McKenzie County, North Dakota. The Project will generate electrical power that will be delivered to the Point of Interconnection. As presently planned, the Project will consist of: Three (3) combustion turbine generators "Turbines". Each individual Turbine would have a nameplate capacity rating of 50 MW. Electrical transformation equipment located at the Project. An overhead transmission system to carry electricity to the Hay Butte substation. Addition of Hay Butte substation metering, and communications equipment. A data collection and telemetry system. A temporary construction lay down area. EXHIBIT C COOPERATIVE'S REQUIREMENTS FOR INTERCONNECTION General requirements for the design and construction of interconnection facilities and equipment specifications shall meet the appropriate guidelines published within current IEEE/ANSI, NESC and RUS Engineering Standards. Standard design requirements include, but are not limited to, the following: Substation: The Customer shall furnish all equipment necessary for the connection, transformation, voltage regulation, operation, protection, control and switching to match the Cooperative's interconnection voltage. The Cooperative will purchase and install the metering required at the Customer's expense. The Customer will own, operate, and maintain the meter M8 within the Hay Butte Substation in Exhibit A. Substation Ground Grid: The Customer shall furnish a ground grid that solidly grounds all metallic structures and other non-energized metallic equipment. This grid shall limit the ground potential gradients to such voltage and current levels that will not endanger the safety of people or damage equipment located in, or immediately adjacent to, the station under normal and fault conditions. Substation Disconnect Switch(s): The Customer shall furnish a group-operated air break disconnect switch capable of being locked in both the open or closed position to isolate the Customer's facilities from the Cooperative's facilities. All group-operated switches shall have a braided grounding strap attached to the vertical operating pipe and connected to a multi-point grounded switch platform. Lightning Arresters: Lightning arresters installed on the Customer's line tap or within the Customer's collector substation shall be coordinated with the Cooperative for the proper MCOV rating. All breakers, switchers, switches and other current carrying equipment shall be rated to carry the Project's continuous full load or output current and capable of interrupting expected maximum available fault currents. Substation Transformer(s): The Customer's substation transformer(s) winding configuration shall be as required by the Cooperative. Protective Relaying: Detailed protective relaying requirements necessary to coordinate with existing system protection and to protect the Cooperative's electric transmission system for the interconnection of the Project must be approved by the Cooperative during the design phase. In general, adequate primary and back-up protection shall be applied to detect, clear and isolate the Customer's facilities from the Cooperative's facilities due to short circuit faults, voltage and frequency disturbances and equipment failure. 8. Communications: The Cooperative will purchase and install the Remote Terminal Unit and Communications equipment required at the Customer's expense. The Customer will own, operate, and maintain the Remote Terminal Unit and Communication equipment by the Control Area Operator within the Hay Butte Substation and Cherry Creek Substation shown in Exhibit D.
